      <hedline>
        <hl1>Death Penalty Messages</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Mark Landesbaum letter disputes June 16 letter opposing capital punishment (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Every time we carry out the death penalty,'' a June 16 letter says, ''we send a strong message to adults and children: that at the very top level of government, killing is an acceptable solution to life's most difficult problems.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Every time we carry out the death penalty,'' a June 16 letter says, ''we send a strong message to adults and children: that at the very top level of government, killing is an acceptable solution to life's most difficult problems.''</p>
        <p>To the contrary, every time we permit a murderer to live we tell our children that his evil behavior gives him more of a right to life than the innocent victim he murdered.</p>
        <p>Executing a guilty murderer has nothing in common with murdering an innocent person. The letter writer uses the concepts interchangeably, and her moral equivocation sends the worst message of all to our children.</p>
        <p>MARK LANDSBAUM  Diamond Bar, Calif., June 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
